{"title_page": "Luciano Bergamin", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=July 2017}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2017}}\n\n'''Luciano Bergamin''' CRL (born May 4, 1944 in Loria, Veneto) is an [[Italian people|Italian]] [[Catholic priest|clergyman]] and [[Roman Catholic]] [[Bishop of Nova Igua\u00e7u]] in [[Brazil]].<ref>{{catholic-hierarchy|bishop|bbergal}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nOn 19 December 1982, Luciano Bergamin joined the community of the [[Augustinians|Augustinian]] order choir lords from the [[Lateran]], took up the profession on 2 October 1960 and received the priestly [[ordination]] on 10 April 1969.\n\n[[Pope]] [[John Paul II]] appointed him on April 5, 2000 as [[auxiliary bishop]] in Santo Amaro and [[titular bishop]] of [[Octabia]]. The bishop gave him the bishop of Santo Amaro,{{Clarify|date=July 2017}} to [[Fernando Ant\u00f4nio Figueiredo]], on 20 May of that year.  Co-consecrators were [[Em\u00edlio Pignoli]], Bishop of [[Subprefecture of Campo Limpo|Campo Limpo]], and [[Francisco Manuel Vieira]], Bishop of [[Osasco]]. He chose DOMINUS LUX ET SALUS{{Clarify|date=July 2017}} as his motto.\n\nOn July 24, 2002, he was appointed Bishop of [[Nova Igua\u00e7u]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bergamin, Luciano}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic bishops in Brazil]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=July 2017}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2017}}\n\n'''Luciano Bergamin''' CRL (born May 4, 1944 in Loria, Veneto) is an [[Italian people|Italian]] [[Catholic priest|clergyman]] and [[Roman Catholic]] [[Bishop of Nova Igua\u00e7u]] in [[Brazil]].<ref>{{catholic-hierarchy|bishop|bbergal}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nOn 19 December 1982, Luciano Bergamin joined the community of the [[Augustinian]] order choir lords from the [[Lateran]], took up the profession on 2 October 1960 and received the priestly [[ordination]] on 10 April 1969.\n\n[[Pope]] [[John Paul II]] appointed him on April 5, 2000 as [[auxiliary bishop]] in Santo Amaro and [[titular bishop]] of [[Octabia]]. The bishop gave him the bishop of Santo Amaro,{{Clarify|date=July 2017}} to [[Fernando Ant\u00f4nio Figueiredo]], on 20 May of that year.  Co-consecrators were [[Em\u00edlio Pignoli]], Bishop of [[Subprefecture of Campo Limpo|Campo Limpo]], and [[Francisco Manuel Vieira]], Bishop of [[Osasco]]. He chose DOMINUS LUX ET SALUS{{Clarify|date=July 2017}} as his motto.\n\nOn July 24, 2002, he was appointed Bishop of [[Nova Igua\u00e7u]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bergamin, Luciano}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic bishops in Brazil]]\n", "name_user": "BD2412", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:Fixinglinks to disambiguation pages, replaced:Augustinian\u2192Augustinian", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luciano_Bergamin"}
